# 📊 Results & Performance Comparison

## 🎯 Objective

The goal of this experiment is to compare the performance of:

* **Rule-Based Autoscaling** (threshold-driven)
* **ML-Based Autoscaling** (prediction-driven)

under identical workload conditions.

---

## ⚙️ Experimental Setup

| Parameter      | Value               |
| -------------- | ------------------- |
| Load Generator | ApacheBench (ab)    |
| Endpoint       | `/compute`          |
| Requests       | 100,000             |
| Concurrency    | 50 – 500 users      |
| Workers        | 1 – 6 EC2 instances |
| Metric         | Response Time (ms)  |

---

## 📈 Metrics Evaluated

* Average Response Time
* Peak Response Time
* Scaling Stability
* Resource Utilization

---

## 📊 Results Summary

| Metric             | Rule-Based       | ML-Based   | Improvement |
| ------------------ | ---------------- | ---------- | ----------- |
| Avg Response Time  | 9.8 ms           | 6.9 ms     | ↓ 29%       |
| Peak Response Time | 2088 ms          | 1500 ms    | ↓ 28%       |
| Scaling Reaction   | Reactive         | Predictive | ✔ Faster    |
| Instance Usage     | Over-provisioned | Optimized  | ↓ ~20%      |
| Stability          | Oscillatory      | Smooth     | ✔ Improved  |

---

## 📉 Observations

### 🔹 1. Response Time

The ML-based autoscaler significantly reduces latency spikes by predicting required resources before the system becomes overloaded.

---

### 🔹 2. Peak Latency

* Rule-based scaling reacts **after** thresholds are crossed → delayed response
* ML-based scaling acts **proactively**, reducing extreme latency peaks

---

### 🔹 3. Resource Utilization

* Rule-based approach often **over-scales** due to incremental decisions
* ML-based approach **predicts optimal instance count**, improving efficiency

---

### 🔹 4. Stability

* Rule-based scaling causes **frequent oscillations**
* ML-based scaling provides **smooth and stable adjustments**

---

